---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Meta Platforms (META) Dividend: History, Yield & Growth Analysis 2026",
  description: "Complete Meta dividend analysis: $2.22 annual dividend, 0.42% yield, 8.94% payout ratio. Track Meta's dividend history since 2024, calculate income, and compare with other tech stocks.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-28"
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description}>
  <div class="container">
    <header class="hero">
      <h1>Meta Platforms (META) Dividend</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Complete dividend analysis for the social media giant</p>
      <div class="stock-ticker">
        <span class="ticker">META</span>
        <span class="price">$525.72</span>
        <span class="change negative">-8.2%</span>
        <span class="date">Mar 27, 2026</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- Key Stats Dashboard -->
    <section class="stats-grid">
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Annual Dividend</h3>
        <div class="stat-value">$2.22</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">$0.525 quarterly</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Dividend Yield</h3>
        <div class="stat-value yield">0.42%</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">Current yield</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Payout Ratio</h3>
        <div class="stat-value safe">8.94%</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">Ultra-safe</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Shareholder Yield</h3>
        <div class="stat-value">1.95%</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">Dividend + buybacks</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Market Cap</h3>
        <div class="stat-value">$1.3T</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">Nasdaq: META</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <h3>Dividend History</h3>
        <div class="stat-value">2 years</div>
        <div class="stat-subtitle">Started Feb 2024</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Dividend Calculator -->
    <section class="calculator">
      <h2>Meta Dividend Calculator</h2>
      <div class="calculator-card">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label>Investment Type:</label>
          <div class="toggle-group">
            <button class="toggle active" data-type="shares">Shares</button>
            <button class="toggle" data-type="amount">Dollar Amount</button>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="input-row">
          <div class="input-group" id="shares-input">
            <label for="shares">Number of Shares:</label>
            <input type="number" id="shares" value="100" min="1" step="1">
          </div>
          <div class="input-group hidden" id="amount-input">
            <label for="amount">Investment Amount:</label>
            <input type="number" id="amount" value="52572" min="100" step="100">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-row">
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="growth-rate">Expected Annual Growth:</label>
            <select id="growth-rate">
              <option value="0.05">5% (Conservative)</option>
              <option value="0.075" selected>7.5% (Moderate)</option>
              <option value="0.10">10% (Aggressive)</option>
              <option value="0.15">15% (Very Aggressive)</option>
            </select>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="drip">DRIP (Reinvestment):</label>
            <input type="checkbox" id="drip" checked>
            <span class="checkbox-label">Reinvest dividends</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="results">
          <div class="result-row">
            <span>Quarterly Income:</span>
            <span id="quarterly-income" class="result-value">$52.50</span>
          </div>
          <div class="result-row">
            <span>Annual Income:</span>
            <span id="annual-income" class="result-value">$222.00</span>
          </div>
          <div class="result-row">
            <span>5-Year Projection:</span>
            <span id="five-year-income" class="result-value">$318.64</span>
          </div>
          <div class="result-row">
            <span>10-Year Projection:</span>
            <span id="ten-year-income" class="result-value">$457.23</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Dividend History -->
    <section class="history">
      <h2>Complete Meta Dividend History</h2>
      <div class="history-intro">
        <p>Meta Platforms began paying dividends in February 2024, making it the last major tech company to start returning cash to shareholders via dividends. The company raised its quarterly dividend from $0.50 to $0.525 in 2025.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="history-table">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Ex-Date</th>
              <th>Amount</th>
              <th>Record Date</th>
              <th>Pay Date</th>
              <th>Change</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="recent">
              <td>Mar 16, 2026</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.525</td>
              <td>Mar 17, 2026</td>
              <td>Mar 28, 2026</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Dec 15, 2025</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.525</td>
              <td>Dec 16, 2025</td>
              <td>Dec 30, 2025</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Sep 22, 2025</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.525</td>
              <td>Sep 23, 2025</td>
              <td>Sep 30, 2025</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Jun 16, 2025</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.525</td>
              <td>Jun 17, 2025</td>
              <td>Jun 30, 2025</td>
              <td class="increase">+5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Mar 14, 2025</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.525</td>
              <td>Mar 15, 2025</td>
              <td>Mar 28, 2025</td>
              <td class="increase">+5%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Dec 16, 2024</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.500</td>
              <td>Dec 17, 2024</td>
              <td>Dec 30, 2024</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Sep 16, 2024</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.500</td>
              <td>Sep 17, 2024</td>
              <td>Sep 30, 2024</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Jun 14, 2024</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.500</td>
              <td>Jun 15, 2024</td>
              <td>Jun 28, 2024</td>
              <td class="no-change">—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="first-dividend">
              <td>Feb 21, 2024</td>
              <td class="amount">$0.500</td>
              <td>Feb 22, 2024</td>
              <td>Mar 26, 2024</td>
              <td class="first">FIRST EVER</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why Meta Started Paying Dividends -->
    <section class="why-dividends">
      <h2>Why Meta Started Paying Dividends</h2>
      <div class="content-grid">
        <div class="text-content">
          <p>In 2024, Meta Platforms finally joined other tech giants in paying dividends. Here's why the timing was perfect:</p>
          
          <ul class="reason-list">
            <li><strong>Massive Cash Generation:</strong> Meta generates over $50 billion in annual free cash flow</li>
            <li><strong>Low Payout Ratio:</strong> At only 8.94%, Meta has enormous room for dividend growth</li>
            <li><strong>Institutional Demand:</strong> Large funds prefer dividend-paying stocks for stability</li>
            <li><strong>Business Maturity:</strong> Lower growth capex needs as the metaverse investments stabilize</li>
            <li><strong>Shareholder Returns:</strong> Complement the massive $50B+ annual buyback program</li>
            <li><strong>Tax Efficiency:</strong> Dividends can be more tax-efficient than pure capital gains for some investors</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="highlight-box">
            <h3>The Apple Comparison</h3>
            <p>Apple started paying dividends in 2012 at 0.4% yield. Twelve years later, Apple now pays over $1.00 per share annually. If Meta follows a similar trajectory, today's 0.42% yield could grow substantially.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Tech Dividend Comparison -->
    <section class="comparison">
      <h2>Meta vs Other Tech Dividends</h2>
      <div class="comparison-table">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Company</th>
              <th>Ticker</th>
              <th>Yield</th>
              <th>Payout Ratio</th>
              <th>Years Paying</th>
              <th>Growth Rate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td>Meta Platforms</td>
              <td>META</td>
              <td>0.42%</td>
              <td>8.94%</td>
              <td>2 years</td>
              <td>5.0%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Apple</td>
              <td>AAPL</td>
              <td>0.52%</td>
              <td>15.2%</td>
              <td>12 years</td>
              <td>4.7%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Microsoft</td>
              <td>MSFT</td>
              <td>0.73%</td>
              <td>24.8%</td>
              <td>22 years</td>
              <td>10.9%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Alphabet</td>
              <td>GOOGL</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
              <td>—</td>
              <td>0 years</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>NVIDIA</td>
              <td>NVDA</td>
              <td>0.03%</td>
              <td>1.1%</td>
              <td>13 years</td>
              <td>-22.4%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <div class="comparison-insights">
        <h3>Key Insights</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lowest Payout Ratio:</strong> Meta's 8.94% payout ratio is the most conservative, suggesting huge growth potential</li>
          <li><strong>Room to Grow:</strong> With Apple at 15.2% and Microsoft at 24.8%, Meta has significant room to increase payouts</li>
          <li><strong>Google Still Holdout:</strong> Alphabet remains the only major tech company without a dividend</li>
          <li><strong>Nvidia Tiny Yield:</strong> NVIDIA's focus remains on growth over shareholder returns</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Shareholder Returns -->
    <section class="shareholder-returns">
      <h2>Total Shareholder Returns: Dividends + Buybacks</h2>
      <div class="returns-content">
        <p>Dividends tell only part of Meta's shareholder return story. The company also runs one of the largest share buyback programs in corporate America.</p>
        
        <div class="returns-breakdown">
          <div class="return-item">
            <h3>Dividend Yield</h3>
            <div class="return-value">0.42%</div>
            <p>Regular quarterly cash payments</p>
          </div>
          <div class="plus">+</div>
          <div class="return-item">
            <h3>Buyback Yield</h3>
            <div class="return-value">1.53%</div>
            <p>Share repurchases ($30B+ in 2025)</p>
          </div>
          <div class="equals">=</div>
          <div class="return-item total">
            <h3>Total Shareholder Yield</h3>
            <div class="return-value">1.95%</div>
            <p>Combined cash returns</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="buyback-explanation">
          <h3>Why Buybacks Matter</h3>
          <p>Share buybacks reduce the total number of shares outstanding, making each remaining share more valuable. Meta bought back over $30 billion worth of stock in 2025, equivalent to a 1.53% yield based on market cap.</p>
          
          <p><strong>The Combined Effect:</strong> While Meta's dividend yield looks modest at 0.42%, the total shareholder yield of 1.95% is competitive with many traditional dividend stocks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related Tools -->
    <section class="related-tools">
      <h2>Related Dividend Tools</h2>
      <div class="tools-grid">
        <a href="/dividend-calculator" class="tool-card">
          <h3>Dividend Calculator</h3>
          <p>Calculate dividend income for any stock</p>
          <span class="tool-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/list-best-monthly-dividend-stocks" class="tool-card">
          <h3>Monthly Dividend Stocks</h3>
          <p>40+ monthly dividend payers compared</p>
          <span class="tool-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/dividend-reinvestment-calculator" class="tool-card">
          <h3>DRIP Calculator</h3>
          <p>Model compound growth from reinvestment</p>
          <span class="tool-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/dividend-aristocrats" class="tool-card">
          <h3>Dividend Aristocrats</h3>
          <p>67 stocks with 25+ years of increases</p>
          <span class="tool-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does Meta pay a dividend?</h3>
          <p>Yes, Meta Platforms began paying dividends in February 2024. The company currently pays $0.525 per share quarterly, for an annual dividend of $2.22 per share.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is Meta's dividend yield?</h3>
          <p>Meta's dividend yield is 0.42% based on the current stock price of $525.72. While this seems low, Meta also returns cash through massive share buybacks, bringing the total shareholder yield to 1.95%.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>When did Meta start paying dividends?</h3>
          <p>Meta paid its first-ever dividend on February 21, 2024, at $0.50 per share. The company was the last major tech giant to start paying dividends to shareholders.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is Meta's dividend safe?</h3>
          <p>Meta's dividend appears very safe with a payout ratio of only 8.94%. The company generates massive free cash flow (over $50B annually) and has plenty of room to grow the dividend significantly.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much dividend does Meta pay per share?</h3>
          <p>Meta currently pays $0.525 per share quarterly, which equals $2.22 per share annually. The dividend was raised from $0.50 to $0.525 per quarter in 2025.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>When is Meta's next ex-dividend date?</h3>
          <p>Meta typically announces ex-dividend dates about 6-8 weeks before each quarter end. Based on historical patterns, the next ex-dividend date should be around mid-June 2026 for the Q2 payment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

